<font color="#FF0000">A TRIBUTE</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 25  1:09:01 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all the vets of all wars,<br>
I wish to express my gratitude to all the men and women who served this nation and helped keep this country free.  God Bless you all!!<br><br>
I wish peace and eternal rest for all the men and women who gave their lives for this country.  I hope their loss is never forgotten or taken for granted.<br><br>
In tribute to those that laid down their lives, I feel this poem best reminds us of OUR RESPONSIBILITY TO THEM.  It was written by Major Michael Davis O'Donnell, a helicopter pilot that was shot down on 24 March 1970 and was declared dead in 1977.  It is featured in the book Dear America-Letters home from Vietnam.  As a elementary teacher, I've read it to my class and I think we all can appreciate it.  It's a beautiful poem written by one of the deceased men we honor on this holiday.<br><br>
If you are able,<br>
save for them a place<br>
inside of you<br>
and save one backward glance<br>
when you are leaving<br>
for the places they can<br>
no longer go<br>
Be not ashamed to say<br>
you loved them,<br>
though you may<br>
or may not have always,<br>
Take what they have taught you<br>
with their dying.<br>
and keep it with your own,<br>
And in that time<br>
when men decide and feel safe<br>
to call the war insane,<br>
take one moment to embrace<br>
those gentle heroes<br>
you left behind.<br><br>
Major Michael Davis O'Donnell<br>
1 January 1970<br>
Dak To, Vietnam
